# Result Handling Rules

## Result Class Definition
Create sealed interface for type-safe state management:

```kotlin
sealed interface Result<out T> {
    data class Success<T>(val data: T) : Result<T>
    data class Error(val exception: Throwable, val message: String? = null) : Result<Nothing>
    data object Loading : Result<Nothing>
}
```

## Extension Functions
```kotlin
inline fun <T, R> Result<T>.map(transform: (T) -> R): Result<R> = when (this) {
    is Result.Success -> Result.Success(transform(data))
    is Result.Error -> this
    is Result.Loading -> this
}

inline fun <T> Result<T>.onSuccess(action: (T) -> Unit): Result<T> {
    if (this is Result.Success) action(data)
    return this
}

inline fun <T> Result<T>.onError(action: (Throwable, String?) -> Unit): Result<T> {
    if (this is Result.Error) action(exception, message)
    return this
}
```

## Usage Pattern

**ViewModel:**
```kotlin
private val _state = MutableStateFlow<Result<Data>>(Result.Loading)
val state: StateFlow<Result<Data>> = _state.asStateFlow()

fun loadData() {
    viewModelScope.launch {
        _state.value = Result.Loading
        _state.value = repository.getData()
    }
}
```

**UI:**
```kotlin
when (val state = uiState) {
    is Result.Loading -> LoadingIndicator()
    is Result.Success -> ContentView(state.data)
    is Result.Error -> ErrorView(state.message ?: "Error")
}
```

## Rules
- Use Result for operations that can fail
- Keep Result wrapping at Repository layer
- Handle all states with `when` expression in UI
- Do NOT nest Result types










